[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is DocuSeal, a self-hosted open-source document signing platform, a credible alternative to DocuSign, PandaDoc, and HelloSign for individuals, SaaS companies, and small teams. 16,500 GitHub stars. AGPL 3 licensed with'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'additional terms for the commercial cloud. Ruby on Rails code base, Docker deployable in one command on SQLite, PostgreSQL, or MySQL. PDF form builder with 12 field types, signatures, dates,'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'checkboxes, radio buttons, file uploads, the standard set. Multi-submitter workflows, so you can route a contract through three approvers in sequence. Embedded signing if you want to drop'

[00:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'DocuSeal directly inside your own SaaS product. REST API, webhooks, seven UI languages, signing supported in 14 languages. GDPR ready, EU cloud option for teams that'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need the compliance posture, plus full self-hosted on-premises deployment for teams that need the data on their own servers. DocuSeal is the full document signing workflow package, so you can run it on your own infrastructure. Upload a'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'document in any common format, PDF, DOCX, XLSX, JPEG, PNG, even a ZIP, and the platform converts it into an interactive form you can drop signature'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fields, date fields, checkbox fields, and text inputs onto. Specify the submitters in order. Send the signing link out via email or share it directly. Each submitter completes their fields and signs in a mobile-optimized web'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'view. No app install required. When all submitters have signed, the final PDF is sealed with each signature and stored in the platform storage back end with audit trail metadata attached. The whole'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'signing pipeline runs in a single Docker container with optional cloud storage back ends, S3, Google Cloud Storage, or Azure Blob for teams that want the documents archived off the server. The'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code base is Ruby on Rails, which means anyone who\'s run a Rails app before will find the operational model familiar. The metrics here tell a story of a project that has found product market fit faster than most open source SaaS alternatives.'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '16,500 GitHub stars, 1,500 forks, Ruby at roughly 40% of the code base, the rest a mix of TypeScript for the front end signing experience, and Vue for the form builder. The latest tagged release is'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version 2.5.3, which dropped on May 11th, 3 days before this video. Release cadence has been weekly since the project went public, with the maintainer team responsive on GitHub issues and the'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Discord channel. AGPL 3 licensed with additional terms. That\'s the part that requires explanation, and I\'ll cover it in a dedicated section below. The supported deployment matrix is unusually broad.'

[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Docker for the standard case, Docker Compose with Caddy for HTTPS over a custom domain, plus one-click deployment buttons for Heroku, Railway, Digital Ocean App Platform, and Render. For a piece of infrastructure you\'re putting'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in front of customer signing flows, that breadth of deployment options is genuinely useful. The feature set is what an actual document signing operation needs, not just the easy parts. A PDF form builder with 12 field types, text inputs, signatures,'

[03:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'initials, dates, checkboxes, radio buttons, drop-downs, file uploads, payment field, identity verification fields. Multi-submitter workflows, so a contract can route through three signers'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in sequence, each waiting for the previous one. Reusable templates, so the same employment agreement or NDA does not get rebuilt from scratch every time. Automated SMTP email notifications when signing actions happen. Cloud storage'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'backends for the signed PDFs. Local file system for simple setups, AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage, or Azure blob for teams that want the documents archived off the server.'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Rest. API and web hooks so your existing CRM or HR system can drive the signing flow programmatically. Embedded signing. Drop DocuSeal directly into your own SaaS product so users sign'

[04:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'without ever leaving your interface. Optional payment collection during signing for invoices that need to be paid at the moment of agreement. Qualified electronic signature support and knowledge-based authentication for industries that need higher trust'

[04:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'signing. Getting DocuSeal running on your own infrastructure is a standard one-line Docker command path. Pull the official image, run it with port 3000 exposed and a volume mount for persistent storage. The container'

[04:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'starts, runs its initial database migrations against whichever back-end you configured. SQLite for simple setups, PostgreSQL or MySQL for production, and the web UI is immediately ready to accept your first'

[04:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'document upload. From a fresh Linux box to a working DocuSeal instance with an admin account is well under 5 minutes the first time. If you want HTTPS on a custom domain, the project ships an example'

[04:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Docker compose configuration with Caddy that handles a TLS certificate provisioning automatically through Let\'s Encrypt. That adds another two or three minutes. Once running, you can connect your SMTP credentials for email'

[05:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'notifications, configure your cloud storage back-end if you want signed PDFs archived off the server, and start uploading templates. Compared to DocuSign directly, the trade-offs are clear and structural. DocuSign has a'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'brand recognition, the most polished enterprise integrations, and a sales motion that has been pushing into every Fortune 500 procurement department for two decades. It also has aggressive per envelope'

[05:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pricing that scales painfully. A small business sending 100 contracts a month can easily end up paying $40 a month. And an SaaS company embedding DocuSign into a high-volume product is looking at'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'five-figure annual contracts. The structural problem is that the signing infrastructure becomes a vendor dependency you cannot remove. Every contract you\'ve ever signed lives in DocuSign\'s archive, and migrating away'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'means manually exporting thousands of PDFs. DocuSeal asks you to run a server and manage your own SMTP credentials. In exchange, the signing flow runs on hardware you control, the signed PDFs'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are stored in storage you control, and the cost is whatever your server already costs plus optional cloud storage fees. For SaaS companies, the embedded signing feature is the operational killer. Instead of redirecting users out to'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'DocuSign\'s branded UI, the signing happens inside your product with your branding. It\'s worth being honest about the license because it\'s the part of DocuSeal that requires the most thought before committing.'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The code base is licensed under AGPL3, the strong copyleft license that requires any commercial fork running as a hosted service to publish its modifications. That\'s already a high bar. AGPL alone is enough to deter most commercial'

[06:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wrappers. DocuSeal adds additional terms on top of standard AGPL. The additional terms restrict specific commercial reselling and rebranding scenarios where someone might fork DocuSeal into a direct competitor of the DocuSeal Co hosted'

[06:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cloud. For individuals running DocuSeal on their own server, for small businesses processing their own contracts, for SaaS companies embedding DocuSeal into a non-competing product, the standard'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AGPL3 obligation applies, which means use freely as long as any modifications to a hosted instance get published. For larger commercial deployments or for'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'organizations whose use case might intersect the additional restrictions, the right move is to read the license file carefully or contact the maintainer team for a commercial license. None of this is hidden, it\'s all in the repository, but it\'s the kind of detail'

[07:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worth flagging before you adopt the code base at scale. If you want to try DocuSeal, the fastest path is the one-line Docker command. Runs in any modern Linux environment, sets up SQLite by default, and gives you a working'

[07:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'signing platform in under 5 minutes. When you\'re ready for a real deployment, switch the database back end to PostgreSQL, configure an SMTP server for the email notifications, and point a cloud storage back end at the signed PDF'

[08:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'archive. The official documentation site walks through the Caddy-based HTTPS configuration if you want a custom domain. If you\'re a SaaS company evaluating the embedded signing option,'

[08:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the API documentation and the JavaScript embed snippet are both first class. Drop the snippet in your product, point it at your DocuSeal instance, and signing happens in line. The repository is linked in the description. If this'

[08:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video saved you a DocuSign procurement conversation, star the repository on GitHub. Visibility actually matters for a project competing against a well-funded incumbent. Subscribe to Awesome Foss for more open-source tools that actually'

[08:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'replace the proprietary defaults.'
